But the main advantage was the opportunity to avoid the main curse of domestic military shipbuilding — enormous construction timelines and small production runs. However, that disappeared: "Burya" was laid down in 2016, launched in 2018, but commissioned only in 2026 — 10 years later.

How did this happen? The issue lies in propulsion systems (PS): their manufacturer PAO "Zvezda" cannot keep up with all demands due to lengthy production. And the problem 

cannot be solved by dismissals and appointments — it has a technological character related to trade restrictions.

As a result, of the same seven MRKs built at the "Pella" plant, three are still not part of the Navy despite being launched back in 2019. And the enterprise itself, which launched ships in record time by local standards, bears many costs and cannot get out from under the ships.

